    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-nov-21-3.jpg" alt="What is the Chagos Island deal?" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The “<a href="https://theweek.com/politics/the-chagos-agreement-explained" target="_blank">Chagos Islands deal</a>” refers to the recent agreement by the United Kingdom to transfer the sovereignty of the Chagos Archipelago to Mauritius. This decision attempts to solve a long-standing dispute over the islands, which Mauritius claims were unfairly taken by the UK in exchange for its <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Mauritius/Independence" target="_blank">independence</a> in 1968. The deal was shaped by a <a href="https://www.icj-cij.org/index.php/node/105778" target="_blank">2019 advisory opinion</a> from the International Court of Justice, which states that the British administration of the islands should end.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The Chagos Archipelago includes Diego Garcia, a critical site for a joint US-UK military base. Under the agreement, Diego Garcia will remain under UK and US control for at least 99 years, preserving its strategic military importance in the Indian Ocean. However, the deal has faced criticism, with some in the <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/donald-trump-chagos-islands-uk-british-us-president-mauritius-london/" target="_blank">US</a> and UK expressing concerns that it could compromise security and bolster China’s influence in the region.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"> security and bolster China’s influence in the region.
</p>
        </mj-text>
